### Why cursor-based pagination is superior here

Offset-based pagination (`OFFSET (page-1)*limit`) forces the database to scan and discard all preceding rows on every page request. On large tables this becomes extremely slow (O(offset + limit) cost), produces inconsistent results when rows are inserted/deleted between requests (skipped or duplicated items), and the separate `COUNT(*)` query is expensive and often inaccurate under concurrent writes.

Cursor-based pagination uses a stable `(created_at, id)` keyset comparison with a `WHERE (created_at, id) < (cursor_created, cursor_id)` clause. It jumps directly to the correct starting point using an index (no scanning of prior rows), guarantees stable results even with concurrent modifications, eliminates the `COUNT` entirely (using the cheap LIMIT N+1 trick instead), and scales beautifully for deep pagination and high-traffic feeds. The base64 cursor keeps the API opaque and prevents clients from forging invalid offsets.
